item.title: Honeymoon horror: Newlywed bride mysteriously found dead in Miami
item.description: A Polish bride's honeymoon in Miami turned tragic when she died 23 days after her wedding. Aleksandra Leczycka and her husband were found unconscious, suspected initially of being drugged and robbed. A re-investigation revealed she likely consumed psychoactive substances voluntarily, leading to her death. Aleksandra's husband has not commented on the incident.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: ‘Coordinated psy-op’: Elon Musk echoes Joe Rogan’s defence of Trump
item.description: Elon Musk defended President-elect Donald Trump, branding criticism against him as a "coordinated psychological operation". Musk echoed podcast host Joe Rogan's claims that backlash towards Trump is orchestrated to distort public perception. Rogan suggested that differing treatment of political figures reveals hypocrisy. Both Musk and Rogan have publicly supported Trump, amplifying these perspectives to their massive audiences.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Is Congresswoman AOC planning for 2028 US presidential bid? Netizens react
item.description: Speculation about Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez running for president in 2028 has intensified, with The Hill highlighting her grassroots appeal. While praised for her authenticity, some strategists and critics question her progressive approach and rapid push for change. Her potential impact remains a topic of debate.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Another MAGA podcast? Joe Rogan hints at Mar-a-Lago podcast episode with Trump
item.description: Joe Rogan considers recording an episode of his podcast from Donald Trump's Mar-a-Lago estate, discussing the idea with comedians and having spoken to Donald Trump Jr. The podcast drew huge numbers when Trump appeared previously, and Rogan has been known for controversial podcast decisions.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Boat capsizes in Nigeria: 27 dead, over 100 missing
item.description: At least 27 people have died, and over 100 are missing after a boat capsized on the River Niger in northern Nigeria. The vessel was carrying around 200 people, mostly women heading to a food market. Overloading appears to be a major factor, highlighting the ongoing safety issues with water transportation in Nigeria. Rescue efforts faced challenges, with teams struggling to locate the capsizing site hours after the incident, said Justin Uwazuruonye from Nigeria's National Emergency Management Agency.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Supermodel Luciana Curtis, family kidnapped at gunpoint, held hostage in shack
item.description: Brazilian model Luciana Curtis, her husband, and their child experienced a 12-hour kidnapping ordeal in São Paulo after armed men abducted them outside a restaurant. They were held hostage in a shack while money was transferred from their accounts. Police intervention led to their safe release.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Cucumbers recalled due to salmonella risk in multiple US states and Canada
item.description: SunFed recalls bulk shipments of fresh cucumbers across 26 US states and five Canadian provinces due to potential salmonella contamination. The affected cucumbers were sold between October 12 and November 26, 2024. Consumers are urged to check for the recall and avoid consuming potentially contaminated cucumbers.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: At least 100 missing, 8 dead as boat capsizes in Nigerian river
item.description: A boat carrying over 200 passengers to a food market capsized on the River Niger in northern Nigeria, resulting in at least eight confirmed deaths and many missing. Overcrowding is suspected as a cause. Local divers are conducting rescue efforts, and authorities are struggling to enforce safety regulations for water transportation in the region.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: UK moves towards legalising ‘euthanasia’ as lawmakers give initial approval
item.description: British lawmakers have approved the 'Terminally Ill Adults (End of Life)' bill, allowing terminally ill adults with less than six months to live to request assistance in ending their lives, despite concerns about the impact on vulnerable groups and palliative care services.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Watch: AI videos of 'Kamala Harris' smoking and drinking go viral
item.description: A series of AI-generated videos has depicted US Vice President Kamala Harris in unflattering scenarios, leading to widespread attention online. The videos show Harris allegedly using substances and behaving erratically. Following the release of these videos, her recent sombre public speech after concession has drawn criticism and ridicule, particularly from Republicans.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: How Barron led podcast revolution became Trump's secret weapon
item.description: Donald Trump's successful 2024 campaign harnessed alternative media, particularly podcasts, to connect with young male and independent voters. Key podcasters like Joe Rogan played instrumental roles in expanding Trump's influence. This shift marked a new era of political messaging, contrasting Kamala Harris's more cautious media approach.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: What's behind global wine production hitting its lowest levels since 1961
item.description: Global wine production is projected to drop to its lowest since 1961 due to climate change, with a forecasted range of 227 to 235 million hectolitres. Climatic challenges, such as early frosts and droughts, significantly impact vineyard productivity. France expects a 23% drop in output, while Italy regains the top producer spot, benefiting from better conditions.
item.dc:creator: TOI Business Desk

item.title: Putin’s alleged love child living as DJ in Paris, claim reports
item.description: Vladimir Putin's alleged 21-year-old illegitimate daughter, Luiza Rozova, reportedly resides in Paris under a pseudonym and works as a DJ. She is believed to be the result of Putin's affair with Svetlana Krivonogikh, now one of Russia's wealthiest women. Rozova avoids public attention following backlash over Russia's invasion of Ukraine.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Why Pakistan authorities are trying to arrest Imran Khan's wife Bushra Bibi
item.description: Pakistani authorities are attempting to arrest Bushra Bibi, wife of former Prime Minister Imran Khan, for failing to attend court in a corruption case involving 190 million pounds. Despite an arrest attempt at her Peshawar residence, she was not found. Bibi and Khan are accused of misusing funds intended for the national treasury for personal gain.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Syrian insurgents breach second largest city Aleppo's outskirts in largest offense since 2016
item.description: Syrian insurgents, led by Hayat Tahrir al-Sham, launched a major offensive in northwest Syria, capturing several towns and villages near Aleppo. The offensive, marked by intense fighting and airstrikes, led to numerous casualties and significant displacement of families. Iran reaffirmed its support for the Syrian government.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Video: Security forces brutally push praying protester from container in Pakistan
item.description: During a demonstration calling for the release of ex-Prime Minister Imran Khan, a protester was allegedly pushed off a stack of shipping containers by security forces. The incident, filmed and shared on social media, has caused significant outrage. The protests began after Khan's arrest on corruption charges, resulting in violent clashes, deaths, and numerous arrests.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Northern Lights could light up US skies on Black Friday night
item.description: Skywatchers in the northern US can expect a spectacular display of the northern lights tonight due to a G2 (moderate) geomagnetic storm. States like Washington, Montana, and Minnesota may see vibrant auroras, with the best viewing times around midnight. Increased solar activity during the solar cycle peak is expected to bring more frequent auroral shows through 2025.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Paris's Notre Dame unveils stunning new interiors after devastating fire damage
Chinese journalist Dong Yuyu sentenced to seven years for espionage
item.description: A Beijing court has sentenced Dong Yuyu, a veteran Chinese state media journalist, to seven years in prison for espionage after he was detained while meeting a Japanese diplomat. His family and NGOs condemn the verdict as unjust and damaging to press freedom. Dong's work includes advocating legal reforms and moderate changes, avoiding direct criticism of China's leadership.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Bangladesh freezes bank accounts of 17 people linked to ISKCON, including Das
item.description: Bangladesh's financial authorities have ordered banks to freeze the accounts of 17 individuals linked to Iskcon, including former spokesperson Chinmoy Krishna Das, for 30 days. This follows Das's arrest related to a sedition case involving a rally in Chattogram where a saffron flag was allegedly hoisted above the national flag, sparking widespread outrage and demands for his release.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk
